P. laevigatus.

Though this species is common at Stockholm where I have collected and studied it for more than twenty years, and though Ι have now compared it repeatedly with the resupinate speei- mens of Pol. iyniarius from Lappland, and though some of them are tolerably alike, I am still in doubt as to whether their identity should be admitted or not. The difficulty is that, if we admit the identity, the consequence seems to be that P. laeviqatus is only a form or variety of P. iquiarius, and this can scarcely be conceded, as typical P. laeviqatus appears quite dis- tinct from typical P. iqniarius.

In Pol. laeviqatus, which in its typical form is a thin‚ totally resupinate plant the pores are small (5-—7 or 4—8 per mm.) with thin walls, while in Pol. iqnz'arius the pores are a little lar- ger (4—5 or 3-6 per mm.) with thicker walls. The spores of Pol. laeviqams are also small (3—5 μ diam. or 4—5 ><3—4 μ) while in Pol. iyniarius the spores are larger (5—7 1β2><4--7μ ), but intermediate sizes are also noted.
